In article <147@vlsi.ll.mit.edu> davea@vlsi.ll.mit.edu (Dave Allen) writes:
>
>What other kinds of natural phenomena create terrain features?
>
>Offhand, I can think of several.  Meteor strikes will result in
>big, circular bays or lakes.  After an ice age, the receding sheet
>ice dumps huge boulders and leaves big scratches in mountains.
>Rivers are natural terrain features by themselves, plus they
>create bays by erosion and deltas by deposition.
>
Don't forget coral reefs...not the most prevalent form on Earth,
but, if you wanted to tweek your animal kingdom, it could be
a big factor.  Also, coral reefs aren't that old, on a planetary
scale, so they would probably be one of the last things to add.


