To: jwm%stdc.jhuapl.edu@ll-xn.ARPA
Subject: Universal Simulator List
Status: RO

This is a long note describing my efforts towards a tectonic
simulator.  What I want to have is a program which is fun to watch; you
start it up and it does an animation of a randomly-generated planet,
showing how its continents drift.  I'd like it to have a number of
parameters so that it could be run for planets like earth - parameters
such as fraction of water, planet size, and so on.  It should have some
kind of text output so you can save results either to look at them
later or to add more details, notably erosion, river action, and
glacier action.

Right now I don't have anything I think is worthwhile.  I have a
program that works but I don't like the results. I also have some ideas
about a completely different technique, with which I will start to
experiment soon.  More on that later.

Here's some info about the program I wrote.  It's based on some
conversations with Mark Isaak and a lot of thinking.  This program gets
a supercontinent splitting up all right.  You can see rifts forming,
and you can see mountains on coasts, but it doesn't look very real.
Still looks too random.  It's about 100 lines of C (not counting
simple graphics support code), and I can't get the code to the net.
These are the steps it carries out.

Take a cylinder the size of the earth (spheres are harder).  Divide it
up into 100 x 100 squares.  Each square can be either ocean, land, or
mountain.  Draw an initial supercontinent.  Right now this is just a
rectangle; one would want to use a fractal technique to get a blot.

Randomly place 12 "seeds" on the surface; each seed will be the center
of a "plate".  Each of the 10,000 squares belongs to the plate whose seed
it is closest to.  That guarantees that each plate is a convex polygon
(all of its corners are less than 180 degrees).  You want that so you
can avoid, for example, making a "V" - shaped plate drift sideways.

Assign each plate a random velocity in x and a random velocity in y, each
in the range 1-10.  Each timestep, everything on the plate drifts 1/10 of
its velocity in squares.  Every 10 timesteps, change the velocities 
slightly.  Thus, the plates don't move but they make like conveyor belts
for the continents.  Raise mountains along the leading edges of the 
continents.  Repeat for an infinite number of timesteps.


I have come across some new ideas for a tectonic simulator.  The ideas
came from a paper Jim Meritt told me about:

> You really want to read "The Supercontinent Cycle" by Nance, Worsley, &
> Moody, Scientific American, July 1988  before you get very far.  I will
> want to use the time since the last supercontinent breakup as part of
> the climatology model.   Besides, it gives nice timing & pattern for
> continental drifting.

I read it this morning.  It is really cool!  I've been reading some
older refs on the subject and I couldn't get a good picture of how all
the mechanisms for continental drift work together.  This article did
it for me.  If you're at all interested in the history of Earth on the
geological timescale, you should read it.

Here's what the article says, in a nutshell.  They have a theory
that says every 500 million years, a supercontinent breaks up, drifts
apart, then drifts back together.  The sea level changes in a fixed way.
Changes in the sea level lead to glaciation.  Changes in the sea level
also have implications for the rate of evolution.  They present evidence
from fossil records, ages of mountains, and geological indications of
historical sea level.  I found it to be very convincing.

Here's the sort of thing I'm thinking about to simulate this.  Generate
a supercontinent (again probably a rectangle at first).  Generate random
fissure lines running through the supercontinent.  Really only kind of
random; you can't have things too concave, and I don't think you want 
junctions more complicated than T's (no X's).  Take the fissured parts
of the supercontinent and drift them for a while, with decreasing 
velocity.  Then let the velocity reverse itself (more or less).  Build
mountains when the continents crash into each other while reassembling
into a supercontinent.

I guess I'm not sure how you get mountains around the Pacific ocean
based on this.  Right now, our continents are drifting away from the
Atlantic.  If there's just flat oceanic crust on the Pacific side, why
are the Rockies and the Andes there?

Well, that's all for now.

Dave Allen: internet davea@ll-vlsi.arpa or @vlsi.ll.mit.edu

