My own contribution, for those who want to design their own languages:

The book _Language Aquisition Made Practical_ has a very complete
section on phonemics and general principles of sentence structure.

The phonemics section describes almost every sound that can possibly be
made by the human mouth, and how different languages prefer different
combinations of phonemes, which contributes to "foreign accents."

(For example, in Spanish, the phoneme /s/, when it comes at the
beginning of the word, is always followed by a vowel.  Thus, when native
Spanish speakers try to say words like "street," it comes out
"estreet.")

The structure section talks about the basic things any grammar has to
deal with, like making reflexive statements or questions.

I don't have the author and publication data for _L.A.M.P._, but you
should be able to look it up in _Books in Print._  A few years ago,
_Dragon_ had a series of articles on language design that were quite
good, but back issues of _Dragon_ are probably a lot harder to come by.

