Article 4135 of rec.games.frp:
Path: aplcomm!aplcen!mimsy!dftsrv!ames!decwrl!sun!imagen!isaak
From: isaak@imagen.UUCP (Mark Isaak)
Newsgroups: rec.games.frp
Subject: Laws of Nature--Who Needs 'em?
Message-ID: <1810@imagen.UUCP>
Date: 6 Sep 88 23:59:08 GMT
Organization: Imagen Corp., Santa Clara CA
Lines: 43


    On the subject of mapmaking, I suggested a method which simulated
tectonics; a couple of other people said forget all that--just draw some
shapes on a piece of paper.  This suggests the much larger question of how
important it is for a world to have a basis on natural laws.
    At one extreme, you have an Alice's Wonderland where anything is
possible and depends only on the GM's whim ("Wha'd'ya mean 'how does it
work'?  It's _magic_!").  At the other extreme, everything follows from
known laws ("Well then, how does magic work?").
    Most people I've talked with think that the Wonderland extreme is too
arbitrary for playing in for any length of time.  But then the question is
how far to go in the other direction.  Personally, I prefer to go about as
far as humanly possible, for a number of reasons.
    In the long run, it's easier to create a world from basic principles.
After I got my continents mapped out, I didn't have to decide where the
best mining areas were, or who were the major seafaring races, or where the
trade routes for the spice trade go--they were all decided for me by the
geography.  Once you have a firm foundation, it's easy to build other
features on top of it.
    Once you have enough features in place, others will suggest themselves
to you.  When we started writing our magic system, for example, we had no
idea that we would also write the "Mages' Compact" to describe mana use
customs; it was a natural consequence of the system.
    Resolving ambiguities in the rules becomes much easier.  For instance,
will the spell "understand languages" help with a species that communicates
with pheromones?  To answer a question like this, you first have to
understand how the spell works.
    Perhaps the most important reason for having a rational basis for
everything is that it makes the world more realistic.  Your geography
becomes more realistic if your deserts are in fact in the rain shadows of
tall mountains.  Your magic items become more realistic if you can give the
exact words and gestures of the spells used to create them.  Even your gods
become more realistic if you have some creation and other myths telling how
they interact.  All this, in turn, lets the players feel that the characters
they are running are living in a real world, not just in a rule system.
    Finally, there's the purely aesthetic enjoyment of seeing all the
pieces of the world fit together.  I don't think I can put this into words,
and this factor may not even apply for other people.  For me, however, it's
one of the major reasons I am building a world.

-- 
Mark Isaak    	{decwrl,sun}!imagen!isaak  or  imagen!isaak@decwrl.dec.com
